{"Id":"b51dac9e04dc42cb83b7733fd952ede1","Name":"Zhaozhou Bowl","Description":"Zhaozhou’s bowl washing and related passages across Wumenguan, Congrong lu, Biyan lu, and Zhaozhou yulu","Tags":["zhaozhou","bowl","koan"],"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:00+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","ParentCollectionId":null,"Passages":[{"Id":"726aa1efb36d4ad9a75ce2d385cbe643","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2005.xml","ZhText":"趙州洗鉢 趙州洗鉢 趙州因僧問。某甲乍入叢林。乞師指示。州云。 喫粥了也未。僧云。喫粥了也。州云。洗鉢盂 去。其僧有省。 無門曰。趙州開口見膽。露出心肝者僧聽 事不真。喚鐘作甕。","EnText":"Zhaozhou Washes His Bowl Zhaozhou Washes His Bowl Because a monk asked Zhaozhou, \"I have just entered the monastery; I beg the Master for instruction.\" Zhou said, \"Have you eaten your gruel?\" The monk said, \"I have eaten my gruel.\" Zhou said, \"Go wash your bowl.\" That monk had an awakening. Wumen said: Zhaozhou opened his mouth and showed his gallbladder; he exposed his heart and liver. That monk heard the matter not truly, and called a bell a jar.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:10+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T17:50:50.5822646+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0293c26","ToLb":"0294a02","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wumen Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"430c8f479a3e492d917d18350e7b38da","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"問：「如何是學人自 己 ？」師云：「喫粥了也未？」云：「喫粥也。」師 云：「洗缽盂去。」","EnText":"Asked, What is the student's own self? The master said, Have you eaten your gruel yet? He said, I have eaten gruel. The master said, Go wash your bowl.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:20+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:51:16.0205038+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0365a22","ToLb":"0365a23","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"f3131d26efde4b43a08df9f2bf0274a3","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"39 趙州洗鉢 第三十九則趙州洗鉢 示眾云。飯來張口。睡來合眼。洗面處拾得鼻 孔 \uDB85\uDD98 鞋時。摸著脚跟。那時蹉却話頭。把火夜 深別覓。如何得相應去。 舉。僧問趙州。學人乍入叢林乞。師指示 叢林 於爾亦不惡 州云。喫粥了也未 渾金璞玉 僧云。喫了 久慣衲僧 不如上座 州云。洗鉢盂去 不得左猜 。 師云。直鉤釣龍。已是不快。漆桶離鉤三寸。已 輪舡子夾山占斷。不道時人無分。大都貪餌 吞鉤。看。他趙州亦不拗折釣竿。亦不蹋翻舡 子。石橋上閑坐。略彴邊度時。自有上岸來入 手底。本錄中。有其僧因此契悟。可謂竿頭絲 線從君弄。不犯清波意自殊。趙州任公。得志 於前。更看。天童鳴桹於後頌云。 粥罷令教洗鉢盂 快便難逢 豁然心地自相符 非但今日 而今參飽叢林客 依舊喫粥了洗鉢盂去 且道。其間有悟 無 一人傳虛萬人傳實 師舉。靈雲見桃花悟道。呈頌於溈山。山云。 從緣入者永無退失。玄沙聞云。諦當甚諦當。 敢保老兄未徹在。雲聞云。和尚徹也未。沙云。 恁麼始得。天童頌這僧契悟心地相符。這僧 乍入叢林。稱大悟大徹。飽叢林禪客。且道。有 悟無悟。此謂之徵問。雪竇云。本無迷悟數如 麻。獨許靈雲是作家。玄沙道未徹。雪竇獨許 作家。徐六擔板。各見一邊。且道。洗鉢盂。僧 有悟也無。太平本是將軍致。不許將軍見太 平。","EnText":"39 Zhaozhou Washes the Bowl Case Thirty-Nine: Zhaozhou Washes the Bowl Instruction to the assembly: When food comes, open your mouth; when sleep comes, close your eyes. At the place of washing your face, if you pick up your nose, and when putting on shoes, touch your heel, yet at that moment you miss the word-head, then carrying fire at night and searching elsewhere in the dark, how will you ever come into accord? Citation. A monk asked Zhaozhou, A student has just entered the monastery and asks for instruction. Zhou said, Have you eaten your gruel yet? The monk said, I have eaten. Zhou said, Go wash your bowl. The monastery grove is not bad for you either. Solid gold, uncut jade. Long accustomed to patch-robed monks. Not equal to the senior monk. Do not guess sideways. The master said: Fishing for a dragon with a straight hook is already not skillful. When the lacquer bucket is still three inches from the hook, it is already the boatman and Jiashan cutting it off. It is not that people today have no share in it; mostly they just greedily take the bait and swallow the hook. Look, Zhaozhou neither snapped the fishing rod nor overturned the boat; he sat at ease on the stone bridge, and when passing by the little footbridge, there were naturally those who came ashore and fell into his hands. In the original record, that monk is said to have awakened on this account. It can be said the thread on the rod-tip was yours to play with; without disturbing the clear waves, the meaning was naturally distinct. Zhaozhou, like Ren Gong, found success in front; now watch Tiantong beat the oar behind in the verse: After the gruel, he orders him to wash the bowl; suddenly the ground of mind accords of itself. Such a swift opening is hard to meet. Not only today. Now, you monastery guests stuffed full of meditation, say then, within this is there awakening As always, after eating porridge, wash your bowl and go. or not? One person passes on hearsay, ten thousand pass it on as fact. The master said: Lingyun saw peach blossoms and awakened to the Way, then presented a verse to Weishan. Shan said, One who enters from conditions will never retreat or lose it. Xuansha heard this and said, Truly right, very truly right. Yet I dare guarantee our elder brother has not fully penetrated. Lingyun heard and said, Has master fully penetrated or not? Sha said, Only thus is it so. Tiantong's verse praises this monk's awakening, the mind-ground mutually matching. This monk, newly entering the monastery, is called greatly awakened, greatly penetrated. You well-fed Chan guests of the monastery, tell me: is there awakening or no awakening? This is called a probing question. Xuedou said, Originally there is no fixed count of delusion and awakening as many as hemp; only Lingyun is allowed to be a master hand. Xuansha said not yet through, yet Xuedou alone approved him as a master hand. Xu Liu carrying a plank, each sees only one side. Tell me, in washing the bowl, did the monk awaken or not? Peace is originally brought by the general, but the general is not permitted to see the peace he brought.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu","Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:30+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:51:04.2234173+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0253a20","ToLb":"0253b17","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"1429722cda4e437ea0bdbf2b14d8a72d","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"師上堂云：「兄弟！莫久立，有事商量，無事向衣缽下坐 窮理好。老僧行腳時，除二時齋粥是雜用心力處，餘 外更無別用心處也。若不如此，出家大遠在。」","EnText":"The Master ascended the hall and said: Brothers, do not stand long. If there is business, discuss it; if there is none, go sit beneath your robe and bowl and investigate thoroughly. When this old monk traveled, aside from the two meal times, which were places for mixed use of effort, all the rest had no other place to apply mind. If it is not like this, leaving home is far indeed.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:40+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:50:59.849224+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0358c06","ToLb":"0358c08","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou Robe and Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"bcf8c596384946d7aca0ea54daa9a97b","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"平旦寅，荒村破院實難論。解齋粥米全無粒，空對閑 窗與隙塵。唯雀噪，勿人親，獨坐時聞落葉頻。誰道出","EnText":"At dawn, the Yin hour, this ruined monastery in a desolate village is hard to speak of. For the morning gruel there is not a grain of rice, only facing empty windows and dust in the cracks. Only sparrows chatter, no one draws near; sitting alone, I often hear falling leaves. Who says that leaving home","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:50+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:51:21.2047673+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0371a04","ToLb":"0371a05","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou No Gruel","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"987019bf169746d992afe2c39f72955e","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"近代長蘆了和尚。天童同參。住一千七百眾。 與竹庵珪。開粥過夏。分寮入室。雪峯三聖。異","EnText":"In recent times, Master Liao of Changlu was a fellow student with Tiantong and presided over seventeen hundred monks. Together with Zhu’an Gui, he opened the porridge and passed the summer, dividing quarters and entering the room. Xuefeng and Sansheng, though in different","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:00+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:51:30.7352995+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0249b28","ToLb":"0249b29","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong Gruel and Summer","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"7f872dfe338d4de8a069e2dd563692ef","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2005.xml","ZhText":"德山托鉢 德山托鉢 德山一日托鉢下堂。見雪峯問者。老漢鐘未 鳴鼓未響。托鉢向甚處去。山便回方丈。峯舉 似巖頭。頭云。大小德山未會末後句。山聞。令 侍者喚巖頭來。問曰。汝不肯老僧那。巖頭密 啟其意。山乃休去。明日陞座。果與尋常不同。 巖頭至僧堂前。拊掌大笑云。且喜得老漢會 末後句。他後天下人不奈伊何。 無門曰。若是末後句。巖頭德山俱未夢見 在。撿點將來好。似一棚傀儡。 頌曰。 識得最初句 便會末後句","EnText":"Deshan Carries His Bowl Deshan Carries His Bowl One day Deshan carried his bowl down from the hall. Seeing Xuefeng, Xuefeng asked, \"Old fellow, the bell has not yet been rung and the drum has not yet sounded-where are you carrying your bowl to?\" Deshan then returned to the abbot's quarters. Xuefeng brought it up to Yantou. Yantou said, \"Great Deshan has not yet understood the last phrase.\" Deshan heard of it and ordered the attendant to call Yantou in. He asked, \"You do not approve of this old monk?\" Yantou secretly revealed his meaning. Deshan then let it rest. The next day he ascended the seat, and indeed it was different from usual. Yantou went before the monks' hall, clapped his hands, and laughed loudly, saying, \"How glad I am the old fellow has understood the last phrase. Hereafter, people under heaven will have nothing they can do about him.\" Wumen said: As for the last phrase, Yantou and Deshan have both not even dreamed of it. When you check it out, it is like a shelf of puppets. The verse says: Recognize the first phrase then you understand the last phrase","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Deshan Xuanjian"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:10+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0294b28","ToLb":"0294c11","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Deshan Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"aa98ef51fc8a4ee7a66f9c361ce11a11","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2003.xml","ZhText":"【一三】舉僧問巴陵。如何是提婆宗 白馬入蘆花。道什麼點 巴 陵云。銀椀裏盛雪","EnText":"Case 13: A monk asked Baling, What is the tradition of Deva- A white horse enters reed-flowers—what are you saying about marks and Baling said, Snow contained in a silver bowl.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Baling Haojian"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:20+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:49:56.1073562+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0153c20","ToLb":"0153c21","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Yuanwu Silver Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"9610485af2744c92a75300dc6d931719","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"廓然無聖 一迴飲水一迴著噎 來機逕庭 面赤不如語直 得非犯 鼻而揮斤 好手手中誇好手 失不迴頭而墮甑 已往不咎 寥 寥冷坐少林 老不歇心 默默全提正令 猶自說兵機 秋清 月轉霜輪 高著眼看 河淡斗垂夜柄 誰敢承攬 繩繩衣鉢 付兒孫","EnText":"Vast emptiness, no holiness the incoming chance goes by a far road is it not like striking One time drinking water, one time choking A red face is not as good as straight speech at the nose while swinging the axe? In a master’s hands, a master is praised Missing, he does not turn his head after the pot falls vast and still, Let bygones be bygones coldly he sits at Shaolin. Old yet the mind does not rest Silently, silently, he fully upholds the true command autumn clear, still talking of military strategy the moon turns like a wheel of frost. Look with high-set eyes The river runs pale, the Dipper hangs low, the night-handle steady and exact robe and bowl Who dares take it on are entrusted to the descendants.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu","Bodhidharma"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:30+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:56:59.4588755+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0228c14","ToLb":"0228c18","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong Empty Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"2d19d0b93276489982dceb650d526c6a","SourceRelPath":"X/X59/X59n1069.xml","ZhText":"","EnText":"","Notes":"","Tags":["zh:釋迦牟尼如來拔除苦惱現大神變飛空大鉢法"],"MasterNames":[],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:01:53.4028554+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:36:05.6917769+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":null,"ToLb":null,"PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"This sounds funny","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":"Book","Apparatus":null},{"Id":"abb74750cf424e38be20299e54c72abf","SourceRelPath":"X/X59/X59n1098.xml","ZhText":"","EnText":"","Notes":"Somebody wrote an entire book about this?\r\n","Tags":["zh:衣鉢名義章"],"MasterNames":[],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:02:39.964888+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:36:37.1386687+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":null,"ToLb":null,"PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"This might be useful?","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":"Book","Apparatus":null}],"Links":[],"SchemaVersion":2,"Concepts":[{"Id":"5a290944b77449139d4e3369f5bbcb29","Name":"Bowl","Description":"Passages dealing in bowls","ColorHex":"#FF8A65","Tags":[],"Status":"Active","MergedIntoConceptId":null,"CreatedBy":null,"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:15:24.1679004+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null},{"Id":"d3393db9d36b4fd9b4a431020b57589a","Name":"Gruel","Description":"Passages dealing in gruel","ColorHex":"#FF8A65","Tags":[],"Status":"Active","MergedIntoConceptId":null,"CreatedBy":null,"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:16:02.9926494+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null}],"Edges":[{"Id":"f42ee41e","FromNodeId":"master:Zhaozhou Congshen","FromNodeType":2,"ToNodeId":"f3131d26efde4b43a08df9f2bf0274a3","ToNodeType":0,"RelationType":"custom-stars-in","EdgeLabel":null,"Note":null,"Weight":1,"CreatedBy":null,"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:14:26.8849643+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null},{"Id":"932ee16d","FromNodeId":"master:Zhaozhou Congshen","FromNodeType":2,"ToNodeId":"bcf8c596384946d7aca0ea